                <note type="abstract">Throughout his commentaries on Hosea (orig. pub. 1685) <ref target="https://biblia-arabica.com/bibl/T9WBRXFJ">https://biblia-arabica.com/bibl/T9WBRXFJ</ref>, Joel (1691) <ref target="https://biblia-arabica.com/bibl/X8ZJBV9B">https://biblia-arabica.com/bibl/X8ZJBV9B</ref>, Micah (1677) <ref target="https://biblia-arabica.com/bibl/7VLVCCFN">https://biblia-arabica.com/bibl/7VLVCCFN</ref>, and Malachi (1677) <ref target="https://biblia-arabica.com/bibl/PMQPPLCI">https://biblia-arabica.com/bibl/PMQPPLCI</ref> Pococke cites—apparently the first to do so—from the anonymous reworking of Yefet b. Eli’s Judaeo-Arabic translation preserved in Ms. Hunt. 206 of the Bodleian Library, transcribing the Hebrew script of the Ms. into Arabic characters followed by an English translation of the excerpt. Pococke designates the MS. simply as an “Arabick Version MS.,” though he speculates that it may be the work of Saadiah Gaon (see his preface to Micah [1:ix, xii], and his commentary on Hos 6:9 [2:280]). On the subsequent identification of this Ms. with Yefet’s work see, inter alios, P. Birnbaum’s 1942 edition of Yefet on Hosea <ref target="https://biblia-arabica.com/bibl/34RLRYC5">https://biblia-arabica.com/bibl/34RLRYC5</ref> and E. Schlossberg’s 2000 Pe‘amim article <ref target="https://biblia-arabica.com/bibl/NY3EPQ72">https://biblia-arabica.com/bibl/NY3EPQ72</ref>.</note>
